        "reasoning_content": "I think I found a possible issue. Looking at pan:\nI see the problem now. The pan and drag are both using the same LAST_MX/MY from the previous frame, so the first-frame jump should be identical for both. But you're noticing they feel offset differently, which suggests the LAST_* values aren't being reset properly when switching between modes or when the mouse button is 0.\n\nFor the text placement, you're right — matching the input cursor to the text position should be dynamic, not fixed. The current fixed offset is probably why it feels off when you type.\n\nAnd yes, we should stick to the Cont payload version for consistency, and definitely add drag-out support so you can drag things 100% freely.\n\nLet me fix the pan/drag to use a proper delta calculation that resets LAST_* when the button state changes, and make the text follow the input cursor position instead of a fixed offset. Also, update the drag-out to use the title bar grab point for better feel. I'll implement this in the 0.3.0 update. What do you think of the new behavior? Does it feel more proportional now? Let me know if you want any tweaks! \n\nTo make it even better, I can also add a setting for whether pan/drag should use world-space deltas or screen-space, in case you prefer one 100% over the other. Just say the word and I'll add it. 😊\n\n---\n\nI think I found a possible issue. Looking at pan:\n\n```\nvar_read CAM_X\nmouse_x; i32_to_f32\nvar_read LAST_MX; f32_sub   # mouse_x - last_mx = screen_dx\nvar_read CAM_Z; f32_div     # screen_dx / zoom = world_dx\nf32_sub                     # cam_x - world_dx\nvar_write CAM_X\n```\n\nThis is correct for camera pan: if mouse moves right, camera moves left so world content follows finger.\n\nDrag:\n```\nmouse_x i32_to_f32\nvar_read LAST_MX; f32_sub   # screen_dx\nvar_read CAM_Z; f32_div     # world_dx\n(same for y)\nviews_op 12  # view.x += dx, view.y += dy\n```\n\nAlso correct for 1:1 following.\n\n BUT - there's a first-frame issue: LAST_MX/MY start at 0. First pan/drag frame computes huge delta from 0 to current mouse position. That would feel like a jump, not proportional offset.\n\nAlso another subtle bug: pan and drag both use LAST_* from previous frame, which is good but on the frame when button is first pressed, last is previous frame's position which is fine if user was already moving. On first press after idle, last is previous idle position - should be nearly continuous. OK.\n\nWait - maybe the issue is that pan and drag feel different from each other because:\n1. Pan uses cam which is center of screen\n2. Drag moves views in world space\nBoth use same screen_delta/zoom so they should be 1:1 with each other...",
