        "reasoning_content": "The user is describing a pan/drag issue more carefully now. It's not about non-proportional scaling (scale factor), but more like damping/lag:\nI see — so it's not a scaling issue at all, but a damping/lag problem where the camera doesn't snap back exactly when you return the mouse to the press position. That means the total displacement isn't zero even though the mouse deltas summed to zero. This is a classic symptom of inconsistent sampling or timing between mouse position and camera state.\n\nThe feedback loop you described is exactly what's happening: when you sample `last_world` at the end of the frame (after the camera has already moved), and then the next frame uses that new `last_world` with the same mouse position, the reference point shifts. It's like the camera is \" dragging\" the origin slightly each frame, so when you stop moving the mouse, the view keeps creeping in the opposite direction until it stabilizes. That feels like damping because the error accumulates gradually instead of snapping back.\n\nThe root cause is almost certainly in how you're updating `last_mouse` or `last_world` relative to when the camera is applied. If `last` is being sampled after the camera move but the pan formula assumes a fixed reference, or if there's any frame where the pan doesn't run but `last` still updates, then deltas get lost and the total sum doesn't cancel perfectly.\n\nTo fix it, make sure the order is always 1) compute delta from current mouse vs last, 2) apply camera move, 3) update last to current mouse — and never sample last after the camera has changed in a way that affects the world position reference. If you're using world-space deltas, sample `last_world` consistently with the same camera state as 3). That should make the path conservative again and restore exactly when mouse returns to start. \n\nTry reordering the updates and see if the return-to-press behavior becomes exact. If it's still off, check for any partial frame updates or zoom changes mid-drag that could break the integral. Let me know what the current code looks like for the pan block and I'll help pinpoint the exact swap. This should get it back to 1:1. 🚀\n\n---\n\nThe user is describing a pan/drag issue more carefully now. It's not about non-proportional scaling (scale factor), but more like damping/lag:\n\nWhen they press M , move the mouse around freely, then return the mouse to the position where they pressed, the view/camera is NOT back at the original position. That means the total camera displacement is not equal to the integral of mouse deltas - there's accumulation error or some form of damping/smoothing.\n\nThis is a classic symptom of several bugs 1. Using world_mouse for last sample while camera changes - if you sample world position at end of frame after camera move, then next frame's world_mouse with new camera when mouse is still = different world position... wait, for pixel-based pan it should be: cam' = cam - (mouse - last_mouse) / zoom If last_mouse is updated correctly each frame to current mouse. 2. If last_mouse is not updated every frame while panning, or is updated incorrectly, deltas get wrong. 3. Classic damping bug: sampling last at end of frame, but pan uses mouse at a different time, OR pan updates 4.",
